The '''1995 salvage rider''' was a provision in the [[Emergency Supplemental Appropriations Act of 1995]] (P.L. 104-19, Sec. 2001, July 27, 1995) to expand [[salvage logging|salvage timber]] sales from July 27, 1995, through December 31, 1996, by exempting them from public challenges under environmental laws. This was controversial because it reinstated numerous timber sales in [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] and [[Oregon]] that had been stopped to protect [[endangered species|endangered]] and [[threatened species]] [[wildlife habitat|habitat]].

